[[sn:Kudatama]] [[ja:管玉]] [[en:Kudatama]]
<!--Kudatama--><!--Kudatama--><!--Kudatama--><!--Kudatama-->

'''Kudatama''' (管玉) are tubular components of {{ill|jewelry|ja|装身具|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/jewelry|qq=}}, classified as a type of {{ill|bead|ja|ビーズ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/bead|qq=}}, designed for threading onto strings for use in {{ill|bracelets|ja|ブレスレット|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/bracelets|qq=}} or {{ill|necklaces|ja|ネックレス|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/necklaces|qq=}}. In ancient times, they were crafted from rare {{ill|gemstones|ja|宝玉|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/gemstones|qq=}} such as glass, and in the kanji cultural sphere, they were categorized alongside other bead forms like {{ill|magatama|ja|勾玉|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/magatama|qq=}} and [[:en:Glass bead making|tonbo-dama]] under the generic term "gyoku" (玉), meaning "jewel."
In Japan, kudatama have been present since the {{ill|Jōmon period|ja|縄文時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōmon period|qq=}}, serving similar decorative purposes as today. During the {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kofun period|qq=}}, they were frequently included as burial goods. Their production as ornamental items ceased by the {{ill|Nara period|ja|奈良時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara period|qq=}}. This article focuses on kudatama in ancient Japan.
[[File:MET 12 37 84.jpg|thumb|200px|right|A necklace with green {{ill|jasper|ja|碧玉|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/jasper|qq=}} kudatama and agate magatama (circa 7th century)]]
== Overview == [[File:Magatamarm.jpg|thumb|A necklace unearthed during excavations, featuring multiple kudatama and magatama]]
The shape of kudatama evolved over time. While Jōmon period examples often featured slightly oval cross-sections, those from the {{ill|Yayoi period|ja|弥生時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yayoi period|qq=}} onward tended toward a perfectly cylindrical form.{{sfn|Ōtsuka Hatsushige (Ed.)|Tozawa Mitsunori (Ed.)|1996}}
Typical materials include {{ill|glass|ja|ガラス|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/glass|qq=}}, {{ill|jasper|ja|碧玉|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/jasper|qq=}}, {{ill|steatite|ja|滑石|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/steatite|qq=}}, and {{ill|tuff|ja|凝灰岩|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/tuff|qq=}}. Manufacturing sites{{refn|name=locs|Traces of place names such as "Tamatsukuri" and "Tamatsukuri" remain across Japan.}} were often located near sources of raw materials, including coastal areas where pebbles or raw stones could be collected.{{sfn|Shimizu Hisao (Ed.)|1998}}
Initially, kudatama served as components for necklaces, chest ornaments, and bracelets, with an emphasis on their {{ill|amuletic|ja|呪術|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/amuletic|qq=}} significance rather than their aesthetic appeal in earlier periods.
== Perforation == To be used as jewelry, kudatama required perforation for threading. Techniques included: * Direct perforation using {{ill|bamboo|ja|竹|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/bamboo|qq=}}, {{ill|bird bone|ja|鳥類の骨|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/bird bone|qq=}}, or stone drills such as {{ill|stone piercers|ja|石錐|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/stone piercers|qq=}}. * Rotational drilling using iron drills, often fixed to a handle for enhanced stability.{{sfn|Shimizu Hisao (Ed.)|1998}}
Specific drilling methods included: # '''Mikiri''' (揉錐): A direct hand-twisting technique to rotate the drill. # '''Yumikiri''' (弓錐): Utilizing the string of a {{ill|bow (weapon)|ja|弓|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/bow (weapon)|qq=}} to rotate the drill by moving the bow side-to-side. # '''Maikiri''' (舞錐): Passing the string through a central hole in the bow, wrapping it around the drill in a spiral, and then vertically moving the bow to rotate the drill.{{sfn|Shimizu Hisao (Ed.)|1998}}
Perforation often involved specialized fixtures, such as a wooden board with a central hole filled with {{ill|clay|ja|粘土|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/clay|qq=}} to secure the raw material. Sand or other abrasive materials were applied during drilling, and polishing completed the process.
