[[sn:Kudatama]] [[ja:管玉]]
<!--Kudatama--><!--Kudatama--><!--Kudatama--><!--Kudatama--> [[Category:Shinto religious objects]] <!--jawiki derived wikidata interwikis-->

'''Kudatama''' (管玉) are tubular components of [[:en:Fashion accessory|jewelry]], classified as a type of [[:en:Bead|bead]], designed for threading onto strings for use in [[:en:Bracelet|bracelets]] or [[:en:Necklace|necklaces]]. In ancient times, they were crafted from rare {{ill|gemstones|ja|宝玉|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/gemstones|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 如意宝珠}} such as glass, and in the kanji cultural sphere, they were categorized alongside other bead forms like [[:en:Magatama|magatama]] and [[:en:Glass bead making|tonbo-dama]] under the generic term "gyoku" (玉), meaning "jewel."
In Japan, kudatama have been present since the [[:en:Jōmon period|Jōmon period]], serving similar decorative purposes as today. During the [[:en:Kofun period|Kofun period]], they were frequently included as burial goods. Their production as ornamental items ceased by the [[:en:Nara period|Nara period]]. This article focuses on kudatama in ancient Japan.
[[File:MET 12 37 84.jpg|thumb|200px|right|A necklace with green [[:en:Jasper|jasper]] kudatama and agate magatama (circa 7th century)]]
== Overview == [[File:Magatamarm.jpg|thumb|A necklace unearthed during excavations, featuring multiple kudatama and magatama]]
The shape of kudatama evolved over time. While Jōmon period examples often featured slightly oval cross-sections, those from the [[:en:Yayoi period|Yayoi period]] onward tended toward a perfectly cylindrical form.{{sfn|Ōtsuka Hatsushige (Ed.)|Tozawa Mitsunori (Ed.)|1996}}
Typical materials include [[:en:Glass|glass]], [[:en:Jasper|jasper]], [[:en:Talc|steatite]], and [[:en:Tuff|tuff]]. Manufacturing sites{{refn|name=locs|Traces of place names such as "Tamatsukuri" and "Tamatsukuri" remain across Japan.}} were often located near sources of raw materials, including coastal areas where pebbles or raw stones could be collected.{{sfn|Shimizu Hisao (Ed.)|1998}}
Initially, kudatama served as components for necklaces, chest ornaments, and bracelets, with an emphasis on their {{ill|amuletic|ja|呪術|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/amuletic|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 魔術}} significance rather than their aesthetic appeal in earlier periods.
== Perforation == To be used as jewelry, kudatama required perforation for threading. Techniques included: * Direct perforation using [[:en:Bambuseae|bamboo]], {{ill|bird bone|ja|鳥類の骨|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/bird bone|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, or stone drills such as {{ill|stone piercers|ja|石錐|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/stone piercers|qq=}}. * Rotational drilling using iron drills, often fixed to a handle for enhanced stability.{{sfn|Shimizu Hisao (Ed.)|1998}}
Specific drilling methods included: # '''Mikiri''' (揉錐): A direct hand-twisting technique to rotate the drill. # '''Yumikiri''' (弓錐): Utilizing the string of a [[:en:弓 (disambiguation)|bow (weapon)]] to rotate the drill by moving the bow side-to-side. # '''Maikiri''' (舞錐): Passing the string through a central hole in the bow, wrapping it around the drill in a spiral, and then vertically moving the bow to rotate the drill.{{sfn|Shimizu Hisao (Ed.)|1998}}
Perforation often involved specialized fixtures, such as a wooden board with a central hole filled with [[:en:Clay|clay]] to secure the raw material. Sand or other abrasive materials were applied during drilling, and polishing completed the process.
== References == {{Reflist}}
== Sources == *{{Cite book|和書|author1=Ōtsuka Hatsushige (Ed.)|authorlink1=Ōtsuka Hatsushige|author2=Tozawa Mitsunori (Ed.)|date=1996-06|title=Saishin Nihon Kōkogaku Yōgo Jiten|publisher={{ill|Kashiwa Shobō|ja|柏書房|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kashiwa Shobō|qq=}}|isbn=4-7601-1302-9|ref=harv}} *{{Cite book|和書|author=Shimizu Hisao (Ed.)|date=1998-06|title=Seisaku Kōtei no Kōkogaku|publisher=Ōta Ward Folk Museum|ncid=BA39973448|ref=harv}}
